actually =status: completed= today with a 9074-char =job_content=
captured (LinkedIn comm/jobs/view/4403039381 — Sundayy / Software
Engineer (full stack) / Tines). It has no graph_trace rows because
it predates Phase 1b graph instrumentation. So the "timed out"
framing in the TODO body is a description of the *historical*
failure mode, not the current row state.

The user's ask still stands as a forward-looking design: when a
graph timeout fires (or any node-level wall-clock budget — see
sibling todo on =ResolveFinalUrl=), keep whatever DOM/text was
captured at the moment of the timeout and feed it into the same
parse path the from-text / paste pipeline uses, instead of going
straight to ExtractFail. That is the path the user describes as
"the most successful thing I built (without AI)" — pre-graph
parse_scrape on raw captured text.

Bundle this with the ResolveFinalUrl-timeout todo below: both want
a node-level timeout that doesn't kill the whole graph. Proposal —
unify as =NodeTimeout=:
- Wrap each node's =run()= in =asyncio.wait_for(asyncio.to_thread(...))=
  with per-node budgets read from a small registry.
- On TimeoutError, route to a single =NodeTimeout= node that:
  a) PATCHes the parent scrape so the row escapes =running=,
  b) snapshots whatever =state.captured_text= / =state.html= we already
     have into =Scrape.job_content= via =PersistScrape=,
  c) routes to =StartExtract= (Tier0 CSS / paste-style parse on the
     captured text), NOT =ExtractFail=.

That is what gives scrape 54's "perfect screenshot" the rescue path
the user wants — even on a wedged Camoufox session, =page.content()=
typically still returns and the text-only extractor can run.

Action: deferred to code; the immediate ResolveFinalUrl bound is on
=feature/resolve-final-url-timeout= (agents) as a narrower fix; a
follow-up todo for the generic =NodeTimeout= rescue path is needed
once the targeted fix lands.

