* DONE Tier1 closed-banner fabrication guard :ai:scrape:
:PROPERTIES:
:CREATED:  2026-05-01
:ARCHIVE_TIME: 2026-05-04 Mon 15:54
:ARCHIVE_FILE: ~/Network/syncthing/Projects/career_caddy/todo.org
:ARCHIVE_OLPATH: Active
:ARCHIVE_CATEGORY: todo
:ARCHIVE_TODO: DONE
:ARCHIVE_ITAGS: IMPORTANT
:END:
Tier1Mini extractor on scrape #251 (linkedin.com, jp 1550) prepended
=**[CLOSED — applications no longer accepted]**= to the job description
even though *none* of the six closed-state trigger phrases appear in
the captured page body (verified: =grep -ic= for the canonical phrases
returns 0 against scrape #251's =job_content=). Downstream, the
regex in =api/job_hunting/lib/text_signals.py:34= matched the
fabricated marker and flipped =posting_status="closed"= on a live
posting, so the UI now shows a Closed chip and scoring / cover-letter
flows would silently skip it. See Scrape Log entry
=[2026-05-01] linkedin.com — Tier1 fabricates [CLOSED ...] banner=.

*Suspect prompt path*
- =agents/scrape_graph/nodes_extract.py= — Tier1Mini node assembles
  the system prompt from the ScrapeProfile's =extraction_hints= and
  =page_structure= fields. The linkedin.com profile's
  =extraction_hints= contains a paragraph (look for "CLOSED-STATE
  SIGNALS — IMPORTANT") instructing the model to lead the description
  with =**[CLOSED — applications no longer accepted]**= when any of
  six phrases appear. The hint *does not* require the model to quote
  the matching source phrase, so a soft mis-classification produces an
  unsubstantiated marker.
- Confirm whether the runner inlines =extraction_hints= and
  =page_structure= into the same system prompt; if so, the closed-
  state block is rubbing shoulders with the obstacle / account-chooser
  block under =page_structure=, raising the chance of cross-contamination.

*Minimal fix shape (substantiation guard)*
- Extend the Tier1/Tier2 response schema with an optional
  =closed_evidence: str | None=. The closed-banner prefix may only be
  rendered when =closed_evidence= is non-null *and* a validator
  confirms it appears verbatim (case-insensitive) in the captured
  =job_content=. Failed validation = drop the prefix; never flip
  =posting_status= on unsubstantiated claims.
- Apply the same pattern to any future "synthesize a structured claim
  from soft signals" hint — generic safety property, not a
  linkedin-only patch.

*Reproducer / unit test sketch*
- =agents/tests/test_extract_closed_signals.py= (new):
  - Feed the extractor a fixture =job_content= that contains *no*
    closed-state phrases but does contain LinkedIn-style ambient
    chrome ("Reposted", "Over 100 people clicked apply").
  - Use the active linkedin.com profile (or a fixture clone of its
    extraction_hints) so the closed-state hint is in the prompt.
  - Assert: the extractor's emitted =description= does *not* start
    with =**[CLOSED= and =closed_evidence is None=.
  - Negative companion test: feed content containing
    "No longer accepting applications" verbatim and assert
    =closed_evidence= equals that substring and the marker is
    rendered.

*Out of scope for this todo*
- Manual cleanup of jp 1315 / jp 1550 (carried separately).
- Any change to =text_signals.py:34=. The regex is correct; the bug
  is upstream — don't make the closed-state detector permissive to
  paper over LLM hallucinations.


* DONE search-flicker fix: invert =loading()= booleans + add subnav skeletons :frontend:scrape:
CLOSED: [2026-05-01 Fri 17:34]
:PROPERTIES:
:ARCHIVE_TIME: 2026-05-04 Mon 15:54
:ARCHIVE_FILE: ~/Network/syncthing/Projects/career_caddy/todo.org
:ARCHIVE_OLPATH: Active
:ARCHIVE_CATEGORY: todo
:ARCHIVE_TODO: DONE
:ARCHIVE_ITAGS: IMPORTANT
:END:
The two prior "fixes" ([[*Search input flicker on /scrapes \[frontend\]][PR #88]] and
[[*search still disappears][the six-route mirror]]) had the =loading()=
return values backwards. Per the Ember Loading Substates contract,
=loading()= returning =false= prevents the loading template from
rendering; returning =true= bubbles the event so the default behavior
(=*-loading.hbs=) fires. The shipped code did the opposite of its own
comment, so on every search keystroke =index-loading.hbs= still
rendered → =<:subnav>= was empty → SearchBar torn down + remounted →
visible flicker + focus loss. Tally #23 territory: prior entries were
prematurely marked SHIPPED.

This change inverts the booleans on all 7 list routes
(=job-posts/index.js=, =scrapes/index.js=, =questions/index.js=,
=companies/index.js=, =answers/index.js=, =summaries/index.js=,
=job-applications/index.js=): self-transition → =false= (suppress
substate), cross-route → =true= (show skeleton), initial load → =true=.

Out-of-scope items completed in the same branch:
- Removed unused =@keyframes subnav-fade-in= from =app/styles/app.css=
  (a relic of an earlier liquid-fire attempt — defined but never
  applied to any selector).
- Added =<SubnavSkeleton />= component plus =<:subnav>= slot in all 7
  =*-loading.hbs= templates so cold loads no longer have an empty
  subnav strip flash in.
- 21 new unit tests (3 per route × 7 routes) covering =loading()=
  action behavior — regression coverage so this can't silently invert
  again. Plus 2 integration tests for =<SubnavSkeleton />=.

=make ci= green locally before push. Promote to SHIPPED only after
parent Deploy turns green and the flicker is verified gone in prod.

